ce:section.ce:para:
Serum UA levels serve as a key biomarker for oxidative stress. Women typically have lower UA levels than men due to estrogen-facilitated excretion, while factors such as exercise, diet, age, and medications can also influence UA concentrations [1–3]. In clinical settings, hospitals commonly use methods such as the Uricase-Peroxidase Coupling Method (Uricase-POD), Uricase-Ultraviolet Spectrophotometry (Uricase-UV), High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC), the Enzyme Electrode Method, and Capillary Electrophoresis (CE) for UA detection. However, techniques like Uricase-UV, HPLC, the Enzyme Electrode Method, and CE are costly, complex, and time-consuming, limiting their routine use. Given these challenges, developing a reliable, efficient detection method is essential. To evaluate the practical applicability of the Fe-CQD sensor, we conducted UA detection and recovery tests using human serum samples. Serum was diluted with ultrapure water to minimize background absorbance and optimize UA concentration. As shown in Table 2
                        a, the Fe-CQD-based colorimetric detection results closely aligned with hospital reference data and those obtained using the colorimetric UA Assay Kit, confirming its reliability. When 30 μM UA was spiked into clinical samples, the recovery rates and relative standard deviations (RSDs) were as follows: 97.3–102.6 % and 2.2–5.1 % for the colorimetric method, 94.2–100.3 % and 2.9–7.8 % for the microplate reader, and 96.5–103.8 % and 3.0–8.1 % for the smartphone-assisted imaging system (Table 2b). Compared with other reported UA sensors [29,42–47], the Fe-CQD-based platform demonstrated superior performance (Table 3
                        ). Although smartphone-assisted sensing can be affected by environmental factors, it still provided satisfactory results for clinical UA detection. Addressing challenges related to sensitivity could further improve its performance, paving the way for the broader adoption of smartphone-based sensing platforms for accessible and widespread UA monitoring.
